1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 c5 4. Bd3 d5 5. dxc5 (5. b3) (5. c3) 5... Bxc5 6. a3 O-O 7. b4 (7. Nbd2 a5) 7... Be7 8. Nbd2 a5 9. b5 Nbd7 10. Bb2 Nc5 11. a4 Nxd3+ 12. cxd3 Nd7 13. O-O f6 14. d4 Nb6 15. Qb3 Bd7 16. Rfc1 {Diagram [#] A similar central break to that made by Karjakin - and with a similar purpose: to activate the knight and prepare a sacrifice on f7.} Nc8 (16... Be8 17. e4 Bh5) 17. e4 Nb6 (17... dxe4 18. Nxe4 b6 $16 {/+- Mi. Marin} 19. d5) 18. Ba3 (18. Rc2) 18... Bxa3 19. Qxa3 Be8 20. e5 (20. Re1 Rc8) 20... Bh5 21. exf6 Qxf6 {Diagram [#]} 22. Rc7 $1 {[Apparently a paradoxical move, which weakens the f4-square for no good reason. After all, the g5-square is already occupied, so where is the g-pawn going? Well, as we shall see, this pawn thrust is in fact a very profound way of preparing Nf7.] Diagram [#]} Bxf3 23. Nxf3 $1 Nc4 24. Qc3 $3 {Diagram [#] [The point behind g2-g4. Apart from Qe6, White also threatens g5, making Black’s position hopeless.]} (24. Qc5 Rf7 25. Rc8+ Rf8 $16) 24... Rf7 (24... Rab8) 25. Rxf7 Qxf7 26. Ne5 Nxe5 27. dxe5 {Amusingly, 68 years later another world champion of the same magnitude prepared a sacrifice on f7 with the same move: g2-g4!. True, the concrete circumstances and purposes of the move were entirely different.} Rf8 28. Rf1 (28. f3 Qf4) (28. Qd4 Qf4 29. Qxf4 Rxf4 30. Rc1) 28... Ra8 (28... Ra8 29. f4 Qe7 $18 30. Rb1 h6 { Ra8,  Nf7}) 1-0


