1. e4 {1) Lasker:The international congress St.Petersburg 1909. (2) Lasker: Der internationale Schachkongreß zu St.Petersburg. 1909. Berlin.1909. (Nachdruck Olms.1989.)} e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Nc3 {The move actually made is to defensive.} Nc6 {Courageously Black tries at once to take advantage of his opponent's too cautious attitude.} 5. Nf3 Bb4 6. Nd5 O-O (6... d6 7. O-O Nxd5 (7... Ba5 8. d4) (7... Bg4 8. c3 Ba5 9. Qb3 Nxd5 10. Bxd5 Bb6+ 11. d4 Na5 12. Bxf7+ $11 Kf8 $11 13. Qd5 Qf6 14. b4) 8. exd5 Ne5 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. d4 Qe7 (10... Qd6 11. c3 Bc5 12. Qe2 O-O 13. dxc5 Qxc5+ $18 14. Kh1 $142) 11. Bb5+ {White plays this part of the game very cleverly. The advance of this pawn prevents the threatened Ng5 and altogether relieves the position of the important Pawn at g4.} c6 12. dxc6 $14 O-O $2 13. c4 $1 $18 exd4 14. a3 Bd6 15. Bxf4) 7. O-O Nxe4 (7... Nxd5 $2 {A gross blunder} 8. exd5 $14 Ne7 9. Ng5 (9. d4 Ng6 10. h4 Bd6 11. h5 $11 Nh4 12. Qe1 Nxf3+ {By this manouver the Queen escapes back into her camp.}) 9... h6 10. Ne4 Ng6 11. c3 Ba5 12. d4 $16) 8. d4 Ba5 9. Bxf4 d6 10. c3 Be6 11. Qc2 f5 {The idea of this is to prevent Ng5, after 12.e4 dxe4.} 12. b4 Bb6 13. Nxb6 1-0


