1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 {Timothy Taylor: '"Though unusual, this variation appears to me eminently practicable.'} 5. Ng5 Ngf6 6. Bd3 e6 7. N1f3 Bd6 8. Qe2 h6 $1 {Timothy Taylor: 'One can already say that Black has equality, with the two bishops (while the white cleric is at least temporarily prevented from moving) and pressure down the b-file.'} 9. Ne4 Nxe4 $1 10. Qxe4 Qc7 (10... Nf6 11. Qh4 {Timothy Taylor: ', levering open the long diagonal, is too strong.'} (11. Qe2) 11... Ke7) 11. O-O b6 {[%cal Yf4e2,Re2c3] Se2-c3} 12. Qg4 Kf8 {Timothy Taylor: '!'} 13. b3 g5 (13... c5) (13... Bb7 $1) 14. Qh3 ({Timothy Taylor: 'and'} 14. Bb2 $2 Nf6 15. Qh3 g4 $19 {Timothy Taylor: '– the key tactical motif is the pin on the fourth rank.'} {Timothy Taylor: 'Black wins after both'} 16. Qh4 gxf3 17. Qxf6 Bxh2+ $1 $19 {Alekhine} 18. Kh1 $4 fxg2+ 19. Kxg2 Rg8+) 14... Kg7 $6 15. Bb2 Nf6 16. Ne5 (16. d5 $145 $1 $13 e5 17. Qg3 (17. Bf5 g4) 17... e4 $17) 16... Nd5 17. g3 $1 (17. f4 Nxf4 18. Rxf4 gxf4 19. Rf1 (19. Qg4+ $2 Kf8 20. Qxf4 Bxe5 $19 {Alekhine} 21. dxe5 f5 $19 {Alekhine}) 19... f5 20. Rxf4 $19 {Timothy Taylor: 'is a beautiful win given by Alekhine.'}) 17... h5 {Timothy Taylor: 'Black has a very cramped game (yes, plus equals according to Mr. Fritz!), but it's also hard to find anything to attack. Amazingly enough, Alekhine finds a way to attack out of this position with Black, though White could have avoided the combination to come with a timely a2-a3.'} 18. Rae1 f6 $1 19. f4 (19. Nc4 Bb4) 19... fxe5 20. fxg5 Bd7 (20... e4 21. Bxe4 h4 22. gxh4 Nf4 23. Qg4 Kg8 24. Kh1 Bd7 {. As Alekhine remarks, the black king simply marches to the queenside. White failed to achieve any opening advantage, and even when Alekhine riskily played for a win, the slight plus White had was never enough to give real winning chances – whereas the resources in Black's position (the two bishops especially) allowed his later combination after an infinitesimal White slip.} 25. g6) (20... h4 21. gxh4 Nf4 $19 {Alekhine} 22. Rxf4 exf4 23. Rxe6) 21. dxe5 (21. c4 Nb4 (21... Ne7 22. c5 bxc5 23. dxe5) 22. Bb1 {Timothy Taylor: '!'} Raf8 23. a3 Na6 24. c5 bxc5 (24... Be7 25. Rxe5 Kg8 (25... Qd8 26. d5) 26. Rxe6) 25. Rxf8 Bxf8 26. d5 Bd6 27. dxe6 Be8 28. Qf5) 21... Bc5+ 22. Kh1 $6 Raf8 $1 23. Rf6 Qc8 (23... Nxf6 24. exf6+ Kg8 {Timothy Taylor: 'Now Black wins technically, much as I did in Hughes-Taylor – with the black g-pawn on the seventh rank, the rook can easily "sacrifice" itself.'} 25. g6) 24. Qh4 $2 Nb4 $1 {Timothy Taylor: '!!'} 25. Be4 Be8 26. a3 Nd5 {Timothy Taylor: '!' Timothy Taylor: 'The hidden point, which White could have prevented with 24 a3 – now Black threatens to take a knight on a5, after which he will be able to capture either White's e- or b-pawn.'} 27. Bd3 b5 $1 {Timothy Taylor: 'The second point: if the pawn is taken either way, Black's light-squared bishop becomes amazingly powerful, as the next note demonstrates.'} 28. g6 (28. Qe4) {Timothy Taylor: 'for if'} 28... Be7 {Timothy Taylor: '!' Timothy Taylor: 'The third point, winning material;'} 29. Ref1 $1 Qd8 30. g4 $1 hxg4 31. Qf2 $1 g3 $1 32. Qxa7 Rxh2+ 33. Kg1 Qb6+ $1 {Timothy Taylor: 'In view of numerous threatened knight forks, Alekhine gives back the exchange at once to reach a pawn up ending with the superior minor piece.'} 34. Qxb6 Nxb6 35. Bd4 Nd5 {Timothy Taylor: '!'} 36. Rxe6 c5 37. c4 cxd4 38. cxd5 Bg5 39. Rxf8 Kxf8 40. Be4 d3 0-1


