1. d4 {1) Lasker:The international congress St.Petersburg 1909. (2) Lasker: Der internationale Schachkongreß zu St.Petersburg. 1909. Berlin.1909. (Nachdruck Olms.1989.)} d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 c6 4. e3 e6 5. Bd3 {The Duras Variation. A similar line of play to this was adopted by Anderssen against Steinitz, but refuted by the latter. It is clear, that the point d4 becomes weak.} Nbd7 6. Nbd2 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. e4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Bxe4 Nf6 (10... h6) 11. Bc2 (11. Bg5) 11... h6 12. Qe2 b6 13. b3 (13. Bd2 Bb7 14. Bc3 Qe7 15. a3 Rad8 16. Rad1) 13... Bb7 14. Bb2 Qe7 15. Rad1 {A surprisingly weak move. The knight is here out of play. The Knight is here out of play.} (15. Rae1 Bb4 16. Rd1 c5 17. d5) 15... Rad8 {Preventing 16 d5} 16. Bb1 c5 {The commencement of an attack conducted equally well from a strategical and tactical point of view.} 17. Rfe1 (17. Ne5) 17... cxd4 18. Nxd4 Bb4 19. Rf1 Rfe8 20. Kh1 {After this move, however, White appears to be irretrievably lost.} Qc5 21. f3 Qg5 22. Nb5 Nh5 {intending to play d4. But first he renders the c-pawn mobile.} 23. Be5 (23. Nxa7 Qh4 24. Be5 f6 25. g3 Qh3 26. Bc7 e5 27. Qg2 Rxd1 28. Rxd1 (28. Qxh3 Bxf3+ 29. Kg1 Bc5#) 28... Nxg3+ 29. Qxg3 Bxf3+ 30. Kg1 Bc5+) 23... f6 24. Bc7 Rxd1 25. Rxd1 a6 $1 {Brilliant play. The a-pawn is thus fixed in its weak position.} 26. Nd4 (26. Nd6 Ng3+ 27. hxg3 Qh5+ 28. Kg1 Bc5+ 29. Kf1 Qh1#) 26... e5 27. Nf5 g6 28. Ne3 Bc5 29. Nf1 {This loses forthwith.} Nf4 30. Qc2 Bxf3 31. Rd2 Bc6 32. a3 Qh4 33. Ng3 Be3 34. Re2 Bd4 (34... Nxe2 $2 35. Qxg6+ $19) 35. c5 bxc5 36. b4 f5 37. Rd2 Nh5 38. Rd3 Nf6 {After} 39. Nf1 {Black would have continued} Ng4 {threatening to establish a most dangerous passed pawn at c3.} 40. Rxd4 $2 {would then have been a mistake, as after} exd4 41. Bg3 Qe7 {Black would have won at once. Black's play in this game is of the highest order.} 42. Ba2+ Kh7 {If} 43. Qc4 Ne3 44. Nxe3 dxe3 45. Qe2 Bb5 46. Qc2 cxb4 47. axb4 Qxb4 48. Qc7+ Qe7 49. Qc3 Qg7 {and Black's game would at least, not have been inferior.} 50. Qa5 {because of} f4 {gaining the e-pawn.} 51. Be1 Qb7 {On} 52. Kg1 {he would have been of better use, as e5 was first of all threatened. At all events, f3 would have prevented Black's c6,} {for after} Bc6 53. Bc4 Bxg2 $2 54. Bxa6 Qe4 55. Qa2 $18 {Black would be lost.} Rf8 56. Qa5 Qd5 $142 57. Qb4 Bh3 58. Bb7 f3 $15 0-1


