1. e4 {1) Lasker:The international congress St.Petersburg 1909. Translation by R.Teichmann (2) Lasker: Der internationale Schachkongreß zu St.Petersburg. 1909. Berlin.1909. (Nachdruck Olms.1989.)} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O d6 6. d4 b5 7. dxe5 (7. Bb3 Nxd4 8. Nxd4 exd4 9. Qxd4 c5 10. Qe3 c4) 7... dxe5 8. Qxd8+ Nxd8 9. Bb3 Nd7 {The advantage of this flanking movement of the Knight is not clear.} (9... Bd6) (9... c5) 10. a4 Rb8 (10... Bb7) 11. axb5 axb5 12. Be3 f6 $2 {A gross blunder.} 13. Ba7 (13. Ra7 Bb7 14. Nc3 c6 15. Rfa1 Bc5 16. Bxc5 Nxc5 17. Nd2 Kd7 18. Kf1 Nde6 19. Bxe6+ Nxe6 20. Nb3 Rhd8) 13... Rb7 (13... Ra8 14. Nc3 c6 15. Ra2 Bc5 (15... Nc5 16. Bxc5 Rxa2 17. Bxf8) 16. Rfa1) 14. Rd1 Nc5 (14... Bc5 15. Bxc5 (15. Rxd7 Rxa7 16. Rxa7 Kxd7) 15... Nxc5 16. Ra8 Bd7 (16... Be6 17. Rdxd8+) 17. Bd5 Rb6 (17... c6 18. Bxc6) 18. b4) 15. Bxc5 Bxc5 16. Ra8 Bd7 17. Nh4 (17. Bf7+ Ke7) (17. Be6 c6) 17... Ra7 (17... g6 18. Bd5 Ra7 19. Bf7+ Ke7 20. Rxa7 Bxa7 21. Bxg6) 18. Rb8 Rf8 (18... g6 19. Bf7+ Ke7 20. Bxg6) (18... Rb7) 19. Nf5 g6 $2 {He throws his only chance away by despair.} 20. Nh6 $18 Ra1 21. Bg8 (21. Kf1 Z0 22. Ke2) 21... Ba7 22. Rxd8+ (22. Be6 Ke7 23. Bxd7 Bxb8 24. Bxb5 c6 25. Bc4 Ne6) 22... Kxd8 23. Bxh7 (23. Be6 Rxb1 24. Rxb1 Bxe6) 23... Kc8 (23... Ke7 24. Ng8+ (24. Bxg6 Rd8) 24... Ke6 25. Bxg6 Bc6) 24. Bxg6 Ra2 (24... Rd8) 25. Bf7 (25. Bf5 Bxf5 26. Nxf5 Rxb2 27. Rc1 Rd8 28. h4) 25... Rxb2 26. Rc1 Bc6 (26... f5 27. exf5 e4 28. Nc3 e3 29. Nd1 exf2+) (26... Rb4 27. Bg6 c6 28. Nd2 Rh8 29. Nf5 Kc7 30. Re1 Bxf5 31. Bxf5 Rd8) 27. Nc3 (27. Be6+ Bd7 (27... Kb7 28. Nc3 Rd8 29. h4 Rd2 30. Ng4 b4 31. Nd5 b3 32. cxb3 Bxf2+ 33. Nxf2 Rxf2 34. Bh3 Bxd5) 28. Bb3 Bd4 29. h4 Rh8 30. Nf5 Bxf5 31. exf5 Rxh4 32. g3 Rg4 33. Kg2 e4 34. Rd1 Be5 35. Nd2 c5) 27... b4 (27... Rd8 28. Nd5 (28. Bb3 Rd2 29. Nd1 Bxe4 30. Nxb2 Rxf2 31. Ra1 Rxg2+ 32. Kf1 Rg1+) 28... Kb8) (27... Rb4) (27... Bd4) 28. Nd1 (28. Be6+ Bd7 29. Nd1 Bxe6 30. Nxb2) 28... Rxf7 29. Nxb2 Rd7 30. Ng4 Rd2 31. Nc4 Rd4 32. Na5 (32. Nce3 Rxe4 33. Ra1 (33. Nxf6 Rxe3)) 32... Bxe4 33. Nxf6 (33. Ne3 f5) 33... Ba8 (33... Bxc2 34. Nc6 b3 35. Nxa7+ Kb7 36. Nb5 b2 37. Re1 Ra4 38. Nc3 Ra1) 34. h3 Rd2 35. Ng4 {Why did he not play} Be4 {preventing White at least for a long time, from turning his extra Pawn to account?} (35... Bd5) 36. c3 $142 Bf5 (36... bxc3) 37. Nc6 Bxg4 (37... b3 38. Ne7+ Kd7 39. Nxf5 b2 40. Rb1 Rc2 41. Kh2 Bxf2 42. Nxe5+ Ke6 43. Nd4+ Bxd4 44. cxd4 c5 45. Nd3 c4 46. Nxb2) (37... Kb7 38. Na5+ (38. Nxa7 b3 (38... Kxa7 39. cxb4)) 38... Kb8 39. cxb4 Bxg4 40. hxg4 Bxf2+ 41. Kf1 Bb6) 38. Nxa7+ Kb7 39. hxg4 (39. cxb4 Bd7 40. Ra1 Rb2 41. b5) 39... b3 (39... Kxa7 40. cxb4 Kb6 41. Rc4) 40. Nb5 Ra2 41. Rb1 b2 42. Kh2 $132 {It is clear that after} Kb6 43. c4 Kc5 $2 {Black would win with} 44. Nc3 {but with} Ra3 {he would have avoided the hampering doubled Pawn, which results from this move.} {He had nothing better than} 45. Nd1 {Why not} Ra1 {and prepare either f5 or d5?} 46. Rxb2 Rxd1 47. Re2 Rd4 48. Rxe5+ Kxc4 49. Kg3 Rd8 50. g5 c5 51. f4 Kd4 52. Re1 Rc8 53. g6 c4 54. f5 c3 55. g7 c2 56. f6 1-0


