1. e4 {1) Lasker:The international congress St.Petersburg 1909. Translation by R.Teichmann. (2) Lasker: Der internationale Schachkongreß zu St.Petersburg. 1909. Berlin.1909. (Nachdruck Olms.1989.)} e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bd6 6. O-O O-O 7. Bg5 Bg4 8. Nc3 {A mistake. The idea to retake at c4 with the Pawn is good enough in itself. After the exchange at c4, White's doubled pawn, even though isolated, would do no harm, on account of its central position; it would hamper Black's pieces and could not be easily attacked.} (8. Nbd2) 8... c6 9. Qd2 (9. Ne2 Bxf3 10. gxf3 h6 11. Bh4 g5 12. Bg3 Nh5) 9... Nbd7 (9... Bxf3 10. gxf3 h6 11. Bxh6 gxh6 12. Qxh6 Nbd7 13. Kh1) 10. Ne2 Qc7 11. Ng3 Rae8 (11... Rfe8 12. Rfe1 (12. Nh4 Ne4) 12... Bxf3 13. gxf3 h6 14. Be3 Nf8 15. Kg2 (15. Nf5 Bxh2+) 15... Ne6) 12. Rae1 Re6 (12... Bxf3 13. gxf3 h6 14. Be3) 13. Nh4 (13. Rxe6 fxe6 14. Re1 e5) 13... Rfe8 (13... h6 14. Be3) 14. Nhf5 Rxe1 15. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 16. Qxe1 Bf4 (16... Bf8 17. h3) (16... Bxf5 17. Bxf5) 17. Bxf4 Qxf4 18. Qe7 g6 (18... Qc1+ 19. Bf1 g6 20. Qd8+ Nf8 21. Ne3) 19. Qd8+ Nf8 20. Qxf6 (20. b3 Bxf5 21. Bxf5) 20... Bxf5 21. Nxf5 (21. Bxf5 Qc1+ 22. Nf1 gxf5) 21... Qc1+ 22. Bf1 gxf5 {22...c5 23.Rxd6 cxb4 24.cxb4.} 23. h4 (23. Qxf5 Qxb2) 23... Ne6 (23... Qxb2 24. Qg5+ Kh8 (24... Ng6 25. h5) 25. Qf6+) 24. Qxf5 Qxb2 (24... Nxd4 25. Qg4+) 25. Bd3 Qc1+ 26. Kh2 Qf4+ 27. Qxf4 Nxf4 28. Bf1 Ne6 29. c3 Kg7 30. Kg3 (30. Be2 Kf6 (30... c5 31. dxc5 Nxc5 32. Bf3 Ne4 33. c4) 31. Kg3 c5 32. Bf3) 30... c5 {f2/ Threatening f2.} 31. dxc5 Nxc5 32. Kf4 (32. f3 Na4 33. c4 d4) 32... Ne4 33. c4 Nd2 {Black threatens Qxh3+.} 34. cxd5 (34. Be2 Nxc4) 34... Nxf1 35. Ke5 Nd2 (35... Kf8 36. Kd6 Ke8 37. Kc7) 36. Kd6 Kf6 {first was imperative.} (36... b5 37. Kc5 (37. Kc7 b4 38. d6 Ne4 39. d7 Nc5) (37. Kc6 b4 (37... Nc4 38. Kxb5 (38. d6 a5 39. d7 Ne5+ 40. Kc7 Nxd7 41. Kxd7 b4 42. Kc6 a4 43. Kb5 b3)) 38. d6 Nc4) 37... Kf6 38. Kxb5 Ke5 39. Ka6 (39. Kc6 Nc4) 39... Kxd5 40. Kxa7 Kc6 41. Kb8 Nc4 42. f3 Nd6 43. a4 (43. g4 Nc4) 43... Nf5 44. h5 (44. a5 Kb5 45. Kc7 Nxh4) 44... Nh4 45. a5 Kb5 46. Kc7 Nxg2 47. Kd6 Nf4 48. Ke7 (48. h6 Ng6 49. f4) 48... Nxh5 49. Kxf7 Kxa5 50. Ke6 Ng7+ 51. Kf6 h5 52. Kg5 Kb5 53. f4) 37. Kc7 Ne4 38. d6 Nc5 39. d7 {was more in the nature of a va banque attack.} Ne6+ $145 $1 40. Kxb7 Ke7 41. Kc8 h5 (41... f5 42. h5 h6 (42... f4 43. h6) 43. a4 a5 44. g3 Nd8 (44... Kf6 45. d8=Q+ Nxd8 46. Kxd8 Kg5 47. Ke7 Kxh5 48. f3 f4 49. gxf4 Kg6 50. Ke6) 45. f3 Ne6 46. g4 fxg4 47. fxg4 Kf6 48. d8=Q+ Nxd8 49. Kxd8 Kg5 50. Kc7 Kxg4 51. Kb6 Kxh5 52. Kxa5 Kg4 53. Kb6 h5 54. a5 h4 55. a6 h3 56. a7 h2 57. a8=Q) 42. f3 (42. g4 hxg4 43. h5 f5 44. h6 Kf7 45. h7 Kg7 46. d8=Q Nxd8 47. Kxd8 f4) 42... f5 43. g3 a5 $17 44. a4 Nd8 45. Kc7 Nf7 $17 {or} 46. Kc8 Nd6+ {After} 47. Kc7 Nf7 48. Kc8 Nd8 {the c-pawns would be fixed, and White's game should be lost in consequence. Hence White plays va banque for attack.} {But it was a condition, sine quo non, to secure the Queen Knight against Ba5 by say,} 49. Kc7 $142 {for the trebled Pawn on the c-file has no mobility whatever.} Ne6+ 50. Kc8 (50. Kc8 Kf6 51. d8=Q+ Nxd8 52. Kxd8) 0-1


