1. Nf3 {1) Lasker:The international congress St.Petersburg 1909. Translation by R.Teichmann. (2) Lasker: Der internationale Schachkongreß zu St.Petersburg. 1909. Berlin.1909. (Nachdruck Olms.1989.)} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. d4 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. e3 (5. a3) 5... Bb7 6. Bd3 Ne4 (6... c5) 7. a3 (7. O-O f5 8. Qc2 Bxd2 9. Nxd2 Qh4 10. f3 Nxd2 (10... Nf6) 11. Bxd2 O-O 12. b4 Nc6 13. c5 a6 14. Bc3) 7... Nxd2 (7... Bxd2+ 8. Bxd2 (8. Nxd2 Nxd2 9. Bxd2 Qg5) 8... O-O) 8. axb4 Nxf3+ 9. gxf3 Qh4 10. Bd2 (10. e4) 10... f5 11. Qe2 Qh5 (11... O-O) 12. e4 O-O 13. Bc3 d6 14. d5 exd5 (14... fxe4 15. fxe4 Qxe2+ 16. Kxe2) 15. Rg1 (15. cxd5 Nd7 16. Rg1 Ne5 (16... Nf6 17. O-O-O Rae8 (17... fxe4 18. fxe4 Qxe2 19. Bxe2 Rae8 20. f3) 18. Qd2) 17. f4 Nxd3+ 18. Qxd3 Rf7 19. Qd4 Qh6 20. e5) 15... d4 (15... Rf7 16. exd5 Nd7 17. O-O-O) 16. Bxd4 Rf7 {But BLACK evolves a fine counter combination, and proves White's combination to have a subtle flaw. Apparently losing a piece; but the resulting breakup of White's King's wing gives him the opportunity for a dangerous attack.} 17. exf5 Nc6 18. Bc3 Qxh2 (18... Re7 19. Be4) 19. O-O-O Ne5 20. Be4 $2 (20. Rg3) 20... Bxe4 21. fxe4 Qf4+ 22. Kb1 Re8 23. Rg3 Nd7 ({and} 23... Ree7 24. Rdg1 {was not to be feared.}) 24. Rdg1 Qxe4+ (24... Nf6 25. Bxf6) ({White would play} 24... Ne5) 25. Qxe4 Rxe4 26. Rxg7+ Kf8 27. Rxf7+ Kxf7 28. Rg7+ Ke8 29. f6 Rxc4 $17 (29... Rf4 30. Rxh7 {It would not at all be bad to push at once} Rxf2 {for after} 31. b5) 30. Re7+ Kd8 $1 {The best was in my opinion} 31. Rxh7 Ke8 32. f7+ Kd8 (32... Kf8 {or} 33. Bd2) 33. Bf6+ $11 Kc8 $2 34. Rh8+ (34. Rh8+ Kb7 $18 {The combination is based on} 35. f8=Q Nxf8 36. Rxf8 Rxb4 (36... Rf4 37. Bg7) 37. Bc3 Rc4 38. f4) 0-1


