1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 ({We think that} 4. Qg4 {is better.}) 4... Qb6 5. c3 Nc6 6. Bd3 ({Here} 6. Be2 {is preferable.}) 6... cxd4 7. cxd4 Bd7 8. Be2 Nge7 ({A better choice is} 8... Nh6) 9. Na3 Ng6 {[%csl Rd4,Yd5,Ye5,Ye6] (This move is against tradition. The usual move is Nf5, with pressure on White's d-pawn. This move sets up an interesting and novel problem, which could be formulated as follows: "Can the move 9...Ng6 be termed decentralizing?" A pawn chain (here the White pawns at d4 and e5 against the Black pawns at e6 and d5) can normally only be attacked at the base (White's d4). Less advisable would be to attack its spearhead e5. So much about pawn chains in general. In this specific case, however, we see matters in a different light. We notice White's Knight at a3, and shudder to think how utterly useless it is once Black has played f6. Therefore, the move Ng6 seems intended to initiate an action in the center, which appears justified. Should it then be classed as decentralizing? The judgment on this question must be reserved.} (9... Nf5 {[%cal Rf5d4,Rc6d4,Rb6d4]}) 10. O-O ({To be considered was} 10. h4 Bb4+ 11. Kf1 f6 12. h5 {but this raid, evolved as a punitive expedition, would be of doubtful value because Black has two replies:} Nge7 ({Or in combinative style:} 12... Ngxe5 13. dxe5 fxe5 14. Qc2 {[best]} Bc5 {and White has a poor game.} ({not} 14... O-O {because} 15. Be3 {followed by} Z0 16. Ng5)) 13. h6 fxe5 14. hxg7 Rg8 15. dxe5 Rxg7) 10... Be7 ({Here} 10... f6 {at once was playable, but Duras likes to disguise his plans as much as possible.}) 11. Nc2 (11. Re1 Bb4 {and the Rook would have to wander back to f1} 12. Bd2 Nxd4) 11... f6 12. Bd3 O-O-O {[%cal Rf6e5,Rg6e5,Rc6e5] (Now the question must be decided whether Black's action against e5 is effective or not.)} 13. b4 {[%cal Yb4b5,Rb5c6,Rb5a6] (With the object of relieving White's position by b5.)} ({Consolidation by means of} 13. Re1 {was also good. In any event, both moves will have to be made and it matters little in which order.}) ({A plausible variation after} 13. b4 {would be} Kb8 14. Re1 Rc8 15. Rb1 ({not} 15. b5 {because of} Na5 {and} 16. Z0 Nc4 {eventually}) {but White would then have the advantage because he has a strong initiative} 15... Z0 16. Bd2 {and} Z0 17. a4 Z0 18. a5 {and Black is hemmed in. This main line of play confirms the impression that, after all, the maneuver 9...Ng6 was hardly justified. If one weighs up the fact that the maneuver 9...Nf5 was available, then from the centralizing point of view 9...Ng6 must be considered a "decentralizing" move.}) 13... fxe5 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Yf3d4,Yc2d4] (Now White obtains the d4 for his Queen's Knight and the premise for the soundness of the whole of the f6 attack collapses [see note to 9...Ng6].)} ({More correct would be} 13... Kb8 {with} 14. Z0 Rc8) 14. Bxg6 hxg6 15. Nxe5 $2 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Gh8h4,Gh4d4] (With this move White loses the whole of his advantage. The truly imposing central island, together with the chances of attack on the open lines, would soon have yielded a strong advantage. The text move 15.Nxe5 is faulty, not only the Black Rook obtains the square at h4 with influence on the center, but the Bishop at d7 then becomes active. If that were not enough, 15.Nxe5 ran contrary to the principle which says: "For the blockaded player, any exchange of pieces spells relief." White has now, at the most, drawing chances.)} ({The correct continuation was} 15. dxe5 Nxb4 16. Be3 (16. Rb1 {because of} Ba4) {with} 16... Z0 17. Ncd4 {though White would lose a pawn.}) 15... Nxe5 16. dxe5 Ba4 17. Qd2 {(The only chance.)} Kb8 $2 {(This makes up for White's blunder on the 15th move.)} ({On} 17... d4 {the intent is to continue with} 18. Bb2 d3 19. Nd4 {and if} Rxd4 20. Qc3+) ({With} 17... Rh4 18. Bb2 Bxb4 19. Nxb4 Qxb4 20. Rac1+ Kd7 {he could have won a pawn and also kept d5 under permanent control.}) 18. Nd4 {(Intending to centralize even at the expense of a pawn, and this sudden and daring insistence on the central idea saves the White game, which was on the point of collapse. Had White thought earlier of the possibility of this pawn sacrifice, he would not have failed to play 15.dxe5, but at that stage he may not have been in a state of mind for heroic measures.)} Rh5 ({If} 18... Bxb4 {White would have played} 19. Qd3 {followed by} Z0 20. Be3 {and} Z0 21. Rab1 {obtaining a position harmoniously blended with both attack and blockade not unlike the line of play shown in the note to move 15.}) 19. Qd3 Rdh8 20. h3 g5 21. Be3 g4 {[%csl Gd3,Gd4,Ge3,Yg4,Yh5,Yh8] (On one side, quick centralizing moves [Nd4, Qd3, Be3]; on the other, rather futile blows on the wing. In these circumstances, it is not difficult to forecast the winner.)} 22. Nf5 {[%cal Re3b6]} Bb5 ({Or} 22... Qd8 23. Nxe7 Qxe7 24. Qd4 {with} Z0 25. Qxg4) 23. Qa3 Qa6 24. Qxa6 Bxa6 25. Nxe7 Bxf1 26. Rxf1 g5 {(Black now puts up a stubborn if hopeless defense.)} 27. f3 gxh3 28. g4 R5h7 29. Bxg5 Re8 30. Kh2 Kc7 {(A Rook ending after exchanges on e7 would be hopeless for Black.)} 31. Rc1+ {And White won on the 46th move. An important game from the point of view of centralization and we highly recommend its careful study.} Kd7 32. f4 Rg7 33. Kxh3 Rxg5 34. fxg5 Rxe7 35. g6 Rg7 36. g5 Rxg6 37. Kg4 Rg8 38. Rc3 Rd8 39. b5 d4 40. Rh3 Kc7 41. g6 d3 42. Rh1 Kd7 43. Kg5 d2 44. g7 1-0


