{[%evp 23,41,-26,68,75,76,0,26,-11,88,79,102,106,468,477,974,955,29991,29992,29992,514] C54: Giuoco Piano: 4 c3 Nf6, main lines with 5 d4 and 5 d3} {Source: Tartakower & du Mont, 500 Master Games of Chess, pp.11-12. All comments are Tartakower's unless otherwise noted. The dangers of a denuded king's field are well illustrated in the following game, in which White, with great ingenuity, gains access to the critical square at h7.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Nc3 {This move of Greco's (instead of 7.d2) is rarely seen in modern tournament practice, as it does no more than secure a draw for White.} Nxe4 8. O-O Bxc3 9. d5 {The Muller attack, thought out in 1898, strengthens White's chances. 9....} Bf6 10. Re1 Ne7 11. Rxe4 d6 ({If at once} 11... O-O {, White has the choice between the thrust} 12. d6 ({and the "bayonet attack"} 12. g4)) 12. Bg5 ({Here also} 12. g4 {is a noteworthy continuation.}) 12... O-O ({Allowing his king position to be broken up. A continuation which has been thoroughly analysed is:} 12... Bxg5 13. Nxg5 O-O 14. Nxh7 ({the only way to maintain the attack, for if} 14. Qh5 h6 {, and Black has nothing more to fear.}) 14... Kxh7 15. Qh5+ Kg8 16. Rh4 f5 17. Qh7+ {(other continuations such as 17.e8 or 17.e2 lead to no clear-cut result); 17 ....} Kf7 18. Rh6 Rg8 19. Re1 Qf8 20. Bb5 {(cutting off the king's line of retreat); 20 ....} Rh8 21. Qxh8 gxh6 22. Qh7+ Kf6 23. Rxe7 Qxe7 24. Qxh6+ {forcing a perpetual check.}) 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Nh4 {The value of this move lies in the fact that the queen can now reach the critical sector with the utmost rapidity. 14....} Ng6 15. Qh5 Kh8 16. Rae1 Bd7 17. Bd3 {Preparing the final assault. 17....} Rg8 {Hoping to consolidate his position by 18 .... g7.[#]} (17... f5 $142 18. Nxf5 Qf6 $16) 18. Re7 {Unmasking the bishop, so that after 18 .... xf7; White can play 19.xh7#. 18....} Rg7 19. Bxg6 fxg6 20. Nxg6+ Kg8 ({Or} 20... Rxg6 21. Qxh7#) 21. Rxg7+ {Black resigns (For after 21....xg7 22.e7+, and Black has no resource.)} 1-0


