1. e4 {1) Lasker:The international congress St.Petersburg 1909. Translation by R.Teichmann (2) Lasker: Der internationale Schachkongreß zu St.Petersburg. 1909. Berlin.1909. (Nachdruck Olms.1989.)} e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2 d6 5. d3 d5 {In zwei Schritten} 6. exd5 Nxd5 7. Bd2 c6 {the square c6 should be reserved for the Knight.} ({In positions of this kind it is preferable to guard the pawn by.} 7... Be6 {White of course has no intention of exchanging his g2 ; but Black wishes to compel him to do so; therefore the d5 and e6 are well posted.}) 8. Nge2 O-O 9. O-O Bc5 10. Kh1 Bg4 11. Qe1 Nxc3 12. Nxc3 Nd7 13. Ne4 Be7 14. f4 exf4 15. Bxf4 Nf6 16. Nxf6+ {This brings black's e7 on a very unfavorable diagonal for White.} ({Instead, he should have occupied this diagonal himself by.} 16. Be5) 16... Bxf6 17. Qb4 Qd7 18. Rae1 Rfe8 19. Bd2 a5 20. Qa3 ({If} 20. Rxe8+ Rxe8 21. Qxa5 Bxb2 {White would have a slight weakness in his a-pawn,} {but he might have opposed the Rook on the e-file} 22. Re1 {and probably escaped with a draw.}) 20... Bh3 21. Bxh3 {His position is weak but this exchange does not help him, but only develops Black's Queen to a strong square.} ({He ought to play.} 21. Bc3) 21... Qxh3 22. Bc3 ({The right move was} 22. Rf2 {Black might then have continued} Rxe1+ 23. Bxe1 Re8 24. Qxa5 Bxb2 25. Qd2 ({or} 25. Bc3 Bxc3 26. Qxc3 {followed by} Re2 $17) 25... Qe6 26. Rf1 Qxa2 $17) 22... Re2 0-1


