1. d4 {1) Lasker:The international congress St.Petersburg 1909. (2) Lasker: Der internationale Schachkongreß zu St.Petersburg. 1909. Berlin.1909. (Nachdruck Olms.1989.)} d5 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nbd2 {The move actually made is to defensive.} ({Here} 4. c4) ({or} 4. Be2) ({or} 4. Bd3 {should be played.}) 4... c4 {Courageously Black tries at once to take advantage of his opponent's too cautious attitude.} ({He might, however, have played} 4... Nc6 {first.}) 5. c3 b5 6. Qc2 ({Here a counterstroke by} 6. a4 {was in order.} {Then if} Qa5 7. b4 Qa6 8. Ne5 {threatening Ra3, axb5, followed by Ndxc4}) 6... Bb7 7. Be2 Nbd7 8. O-O Qc7 9. Re1 e6 10. Bf1 Bd6 11. g3 h6 {The idea of this is to prevent Ng5, after 12.e4 dxe4.} 12. Bg2 O-O 13. Nh4 Ne4 $2 {A gross blunder} ({By} 13... g5 14. Nhf3 Ne4 15. Z0 f5 {Black would have obtained a strong attacking position.}) 14. Nxe4 $14 dxe4 15. Bxe4 g5 16. Ng2 e5 17. Bxb7 Qxb7 18. Qf5 $16 (18. e4 $16) 18... e4 19. Bd2 (19. a4 $16) 19... Be7 20. Rf1 (20. h4 $14) 20... Nf6 $11 21. f4 g4 (21... exf3 22. Rxf3 Ne4 $11) 22. Qe5 {By this manouver the Queen escapes back into her camp.} Rad8 23. f5 Rd5 24. Qf4 Kg7 25. Qf2 Nh7 26. Qe2 h5 27. h3 {White plays this part of the game very cleverly. The advance of this pawn prevents the threatened Ng5 and altogether relieves the position of the important Pawn at g4.} gxh3 (27... Nf6 $11) 28. Nf4 $14 Ng5 $2 (28... Rd6 $142 29. a4 (29. Nxh3 $11 Rg8 30. Be1 Rh6) (29. Kh1 Rh6 $11) (29. Nxh5+ Kh8 30. f6 Bxf6 31. Nxf6 Nxf6 32. Rf5 Kg7 $11) 29... Ng5 30. axb5 Nf3+ 31. Kh1 Rh6 32. Bc1 Qxb5 33. Rxa7 Re8 34. b4 Qxf5 $11) 29. f6+ $1 $18 Bxf6 30. Nxh5+ Kg6 31. Nxf6 (31. Rxf6+ $18) 31... Nf3+ 32. Rxf3 exf3 33. Qxf3 Rd7 34. e4 1-0


