1. e4 {1) Lasker:The international congress St.Petersburg 1909. (2) Lasker: Der internationale Schachkongreß zu St.Petersburg. 1909. Berlin.1909. (Nachdruck Olms.1989.)} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. c4 {The Duras Variation. A similar line of play to this was adopted by Anderssen against Steinitz, but refuted by the latter. It is clear, that the point d4 becomes weak.} g6 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bh4 O-O 12. O-O Re8 13. Re1 Rb8 14. Rb1 c5 15. Nb3 {A surprisingly weak move. The knight is here out of play. The Knight is here out of play.} ({On} 15. Nf3 {he would have been of better use, as e5 was first of all threatened. At all events, f3 would have prevented Black's c6,} {for after} Bc6 16. e5 Bxf3 $2 (16... dxe5 $142 17. Nxe5 Ba8 18. Qa4 Qc8 $15 19. Qxa7 $2 Nh5 $19 20. Qxc5 Qf5 21. Qxc7 Bxe5 22. Rxe5 Qxe5 23. Qxe5 Rxe5) 17. Qxf3 dxe5 18. Rbd1 $18 {Black would be lost.} Qe7 19. Nd5) 15... Bc6 {Preventing 16 d5} 16. Qd3 (16. Nd5 {because of} g5 {gaining the e-pawn.} 17. Bg3 Rxe4) 16... Qc8 {The commencement of an attack conducted equally well from a strategical and tactical point of view.} 17. Nd2 Nd7 18. b3 Qa6 19. Qc2 Qa5 20. Ne2 {After this move, however, White appears to be irretrievably lost.} ({If} 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. cxd5 Qc3 22. Rbc1 Qxc2 23. Rxc2 g5 24. Bg3 f5 25. f3 f4 26. Bf2 Ne5 {and Black's game would at least, not have been inferior.}) 20... Nf8 21. f3 Ne6 22. Bf2 Bd7 {intending to play d4. But first he renders the c-pawn mobile.} 23. Nf1 Nd4 24. Qd3 Nc6 25. Nc1 Qa3 $1 {Brilliant play. The a-pawn is thus fixed in its weak position.} 26. Ne3 Nb4 27. Qd2 a5 28. Nd5 Nxd5 29. exd5 {This loses forthwith.} ({After} 29. cxd5 {Black would have continued} c4 {threatening to establish a most dangerous passed pawn at c3.} 30. Bd4 $2 {would then have been a mistake, as after} Qb4 31. Rd1 (31. Qxb4 Bxd4+) 31... c3 {Black would have won at once. Black's play in this game is of the highest order.}) 29... Rxe1+ 30. Bxe1 Bf5 31. Nd3 Bxd3 32. Qxd3 Qxa2 33. h3 a4 34. b4 cxb4 35. Rxb4 Rxb4 36. Bxb4 Qb3 37. Qd2 a3 38. Bxa3 Qxa3 0-1


