1. d4 {1) Lasker:The international congress St.Petersburg 1909. Translation by R.Teichmann. (2) Lasker: Der internationale Schachkongreß zu St.Petersburg. 1909. Berlin.1909. (Nachdruck Olms.1989.)} d5 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 a6 4. c4 dxc4 5. Bxc4 b5 6. Bd3 Bb7 7. O-O Nf6 8. Nc3 Nbd7 9. Qe2 c5 10. b3 ({It would not at all be bad to push at once} 10. e4 {for after} cxd4 ({and} 10... c4 11. Bc2 {was not to be feared.}) 11. Nxd4 Nc5 {White would play} 12. Rd1) 10... Bd6 11. Bb2 Qb6 12. Rad1 Rc8 13. Bb1 O-O 14. e4 cxd4 15. Rxd4 Ne5 16. Rxd6 Nxf3+ {But BLACK evolves a fine counter combination, and proves White's combination to have a subtle flaw. Apparently losing a piece; but the resulting breakup of White's King's wing gives him the opportunity for a dangerous attack.} ({The combination is based on} 16... Qxd6 17. Nxe5 Qxe5 18. Nd5 Qg5 19. f4 Qh6 20. Nxf6+ ({or} 20. Ne7+ Kh8 21. Nxc8) 20... gxf6 21. Rf3) 17. gxf3 Qxd6 18. e5 Qb4 19. exf6 Rxc3 20. Qe5 $2 (20. Qd2 Bxf3 21. Qg5 g6 22. h3 (22. a3 Rc5 $1) 22... Rfc8 $17) ({The best was in my opinion} 20. fxg7 Rd8 (20... Bxf3 $2 21. gxf8=Q+ Kxf8 22. Qe5 $18) 21. Bxc3 Qxc3 22. Rd1 $11) 20... Rc5 21. Qe3 Rh5 22. fxg7 Rc8 23. Rd1 Qh4 24. Rd7 Qxh2+ 25. Kf1 Qh1+ 26. Ke2 Qxb1 0-1


