1. e4 {Stohl,Igor Stohl, Igor Stohl Zenón Franco: 'Lasker,Em/Gelfand: 'Stohl,Igor'' (1)Kmoch: Rubinstein gewinnt! S.48. (2) Lasker: Der internationale Schachkongreß zu St.Petersburg. 1909. Berlin.1909. (Nachdruck Olms.1989.) S.79. Zenón Franco: 'Lasker,Em/Gelfand: '(1)Kmoch: Rubinstein gewinnt! S.48. (2) Lasker: Der internationale Schachkongreß zu St.Petersburg. 1909. Berlin.1909. (Nachdruck Olms.1989.) S.79.''} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. c4 {Das Duras System. Zenón Franco: 'Duras was fond of this pawn structure, with which he gained many victories. Lasker,Em/Gelfand: 'Das Duras System.'' Lasker: Dieser Modus der Entwicklung ist wenig mehr als ein Tempoverlust. Schwarz bringt dabei seine Figuren schneller ins Spiel als Weiß. Kmoch: Die Lieblingsvariante des tschechischen Meisters. Er hat mit ihr viele Erfolge errungen. Zenón Franco: 'Lasker,Em/Gelfand: 'Lasker: Dieser Modus der Entwicklung ist wenig mehr als ein Tempoverlust. Schwarz bringt dabei seine Figuren schneller ins Spiel als Weiß. Kmoch: Die Lieblingsvariante des tschechischen Meisters. Er hat mit ihr viele Erfolge errungen.''} (6. c3) 6... g6 ({Zenón Franco: 'The alternatives are'} 6... Be7 {Stohl} 7. h3 O-O 8. Be3 Ne8 (8... Nd7 $5 9. Nc3 Bf6 10. Ne2 Nc5 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Bxc5 dxc5 13. Qb3 Qd6 $13 {1/2,Ricardi,P (2544)-Morovic Fernandez,I (2554)/Pinamar/2002/}) 9. Nc3 f5 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. d4 fxe4 12. Nxe4 exd4 13. Nxd4 Bd7 14. Qc2 c5 15. Ne2 Nf6 16. N4c3 Qc8 17. f3 Bf5 18. Qd2 Nd7 19. O-O Ne5 20. b3 Qd7 21. f4 Nc6 22. Rad1 Rae8 $132 {Yudasin,L (2645)-Beliavsky,A (2640)/Munich/1991/}) ({Zenón Franco: 'and'} 6... Bg4 $5 {Stohl Zenón Franco: '. Lasker,Em/Gelfand: '!?' Lasker,Em/Gelfand: 'Stohl,Igor'' Stohl,Igor: 'is a standard reaction against the Duras setup in the Steinitz Defence. Here Black must reckon with the possible bd2 development, although it shouldn't be too dangerous:' is a standard reaction against the Duras setup in the Steinitz Defence. Here Black must reckon with the possible bd2 development, although it shouldn't be too dangerous: Zenón Franco: 'Lasker,Em/Gelfand: 'is a standard reaction against the Duras setup in the Steinitz Defence. Here Black must reckon with the possible bd2 development, although it shouldn't be too dangerous:''} 7. Be3 (7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nd7 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. O-O Be7 11. Nc3 {Panarin,M (2486)-Malaniuk,V (2513)/Krasnodar/2005/} Bg5 $11) 7... Be7 (7... Nd7 8. Nbd2 Be7 (8... Nc5 $2 9. Bxc5 dxc5 10. Qb3 $16) 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Nxf3 Bf6 11. O-O O-O 12. b4 $5 Nd4 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Bd2 c6 15. Bb3 c5 16. a3 b6 17. f4 Qe7 18. Ba4 Nb8 19. bxc5 bxc5 20. Rb1 Qc7 21. Qf3 Ra7 22. Rb3 Rc8 23. Rfb1 $36 {Vasiukov,E (2505)-Frumson,Y (2275)/Bad Liebenzell/1996/}) 8. Nbd2 $5 (8. Nc3 O-O 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nd7 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. O-O Bg5 13. Rad1 Rb8 14. b3 Qe7 15. Qg4 Bxe3 16. fxe3 Rbe8 17. Rf2 a5 18. Re2 Qd8 19. d4 Re6 20. Rf1 Rg6 21. Qh5 exd4 $1 22. exd4 c5 $15 {Mekhitarian,K (2258)-Tomashevsky,E (2523)/WChJ Heraklio/2004/}) 8... O-O 9. h3 Bh5 10. g4 Bg6 11. Nh4 (11. Nf1 b5 $5 12. cxb5 axb5 13. Bxb5 Nb4 $44 {Amonatov,F (2569)-Novikov,M (2489)/Moscow/2006/}) 11... Nd7 12. Nf5 Bxf5 13. gxf5 Bg5 14. Qg4 Bxe3 15. fxe3 Nc5 (15... b5 $1 16. cxb5 Nb4 $44) 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. Rg1 Qf6 18. Ke2 Kh8 19. Qh5 Rab8 20. b3 Rbd8 21. Rac1 g6 22. Qh6 Qg7 23. Qh4 $14 {Duras,O-Dusek,A/Plzen/1911/}) 7. d4 {Zenón Franco: 'Now what we have on the board is a sort of King's Indian, with White's bishop placed on a4 instead of e2, which gives an original twist to the position.' Stohl,Igor: 'If White refrains from immediate central expansion, Black, according to cicumstances, can seek active  himself on both flanks:' Stohl: 'If White refrains from immediate central expansion, Black, according to cicumstances, can seek active  himself on both flanks:' Zenón Franco: 'Lasker,Em/Gelfand: 'Stohl,Igor: 'If White refrains from immediate central expansion, Black, according to cicumstances, can seek active  himself on both flanks:'''} ({Zenón Franco: 'Another possibility, also tried by Duras, is'} 7. Nc3 $11 {Zenón Franco: 'without opening the centre. He used to play this with the idea of castling queenside if appropriate and then attacking Black's kingside. In that case it suits White to keep the g7-bishop quiet, given the weakness created by playing c2-c4. Lasker,Em/Gelfand: '=''} Bg7 {Stohl Zenón Franco: 'Stohl,Igor'} 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bd2 O-O 10. h3 Nd7 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Qe2 Nc5 13. Be3 Ne6 14. Qd2 Kh7 15. g4 c5 16. O-O-O Rb8 17. Rdg1 c6 18. Kb1 Bd7 19. h4 Rb4 20. Ne1 Qb6 21. f3 Rb8 22. Rg2 a5 23. Qc1 a4 24. Ka1 Qb7 25. Nd1 Rb6 26. Nc2 Nc7 27. Na3 Ne6 28. Nc3 Rb4 29. Qc2 Qa8 30. Rb1 Nd4 31. Bxd4 cxd4 32. Ne2 d5 $36 {,,Duras,O-Maroczy,G/Vienna/1908/ Stohl,Igor: ',,Duras,O-Maroczy,G/Vienna/1908/'}) (7. h3 {Stohl Zenón Franco: 'Stohl,Igor'} Bg7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Be3 Nd7 $5 (9... Bd7 10. Qd2 Kh8 (10... Ne8 11. h4 Nd4 12. Bd1 Bg4 13. Nxd4 Bxd1 14. Nde2 Bxe2 15. Nxe2 f5 16. Bg5 Bf6 17. Bh6 Bg7 18. h5 f4 19. hxg6 hxg6 20. O-O-O Bxh6 21. Rxh6 Qg5 22. Rh2 Ng7 23. Rdh1 $36 {Duras,O-Yates,F/Bradford/1911/}) 11. O-O Nh5 12. d4 exd4 13. Nxd4 Ne5 14. Bb3 c5 15. Nde2 Be6 16. Nd5 Bxd5 17. cxd5 f5 18. exf5 gxf5 19. Rae1 Rg8 20. f4 Ng6 21. Kh2 Qf6 $13 {Kupreichik,V (2570)-Tseshkovsky,V (2595)/Severodonetsk/1982/}) 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Qd2 f5 $132 12. exf5 gxf5 13. Bh6 Bxh6 14. Qxh6 Qf6 15. Qxf6 Nxf6 16. d4 e4 17. Nd2 f4 18. f3 e3 19. Nde4 Bf5 20. Ke2 Rae8 21. Nxf6+ Rxf6 22. g3 $1 fxg3 23. Rag1 Rg6 24. Rg2 Kf7 25. h4 Kf6 26. Rhg1 Rh6 27. Rh1 Rg6 {Yudasin,L (2645)-Huebner,R (2620)/Munich/1991/} 28. Rhg1 $11) 7... exd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 9. Nxc6 (9. Bxc6 bxc6 $11) (9. Nc3 {Stohl Zenón Franco: 'Stohl,Igor'} Bg7 10. Nxc6 Bxc6 (10... bxc6 $5 11. O-O O-O 12. c5 {transposes to 9.c6 bxc6!?}) 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Qa4 Qd7 13. O-O O-O 14. Rd1 (14. Bg5 Rfe8 15. c5 dxc5 $5 16. Be3 Qe6 17. f3 c4 18. Rfd1 Nd7 19. Bd4 Ne5 20. Qa5 Nd3 $36 {Perunovic,M (2562)-Almasi,Z (2675)/Vogosca/2007/}) 14... Nh5 (14... Rfe8 $132) 15. c5 f5 16. cxd6 cxd6 17. exf5 gxf5 18. Qh4 Qe8 19. Bg