1. e4 {Alekhine} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 bxc6 {Timothy Taylor: '"Though unusual, this variation appears to me eminently practicable.'} ({"In any case it has the advantage of not allowing White the majority of pawns on the kingside as happens after} 4... dxc6 5. d4 exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4 {etc," writes Alekhine. I couldn't agree more!}) 5. d4 exd4 6. Qxd4 Qf6 (6... c5 {is one move I don't recommend: although good in Chapter Six, here the missing tempo counts, as White has a nasty check:} 7. Qe5+ {(obviously not possible when the black d-pawn is already on d6!)} Qe7 ({the only move that doesn't lose a pawn: if} 7... Be7 8. Qxg7) ({, or} 7... Ne7 8. Qxc5) 8. Qxc7 Qxe4+ 9. Be3 ({weaker is} 9. Kd1 Qd5+ 10. Bd2 Bd6 {with counterplay in Y.Gusev-V.Shcherbakov, Moscow 1955}) 9... Qxc2 10. Nc3 Qxb2 11. Qe5+ Ne7 12. Rb1 Qc2 13. Bxc5 {and White has more than enough for the pawn.}) (6... Ne7 7. Nc3 Ng6 {(as in the previous game, the solid Knight Defence development works well here)} 8. h4 h5 9. Bg5 f6 10. Bd2 Qe7 11. O-O-O Qc5 12. Qd3 Qd6 13. Qe3 Qc5 14. Qe2 Ne5 {(it's true that Black gained ground by threatening to draw with queen repetitions, but now has obtained an ideal position)} 15. Bf4 d6 16. Be3 ({or} 16. Nxe5 fxe5 17. Be3 Qa5 18. Qc4 Bd7 19. Qb3 Be7 20. Kb1 Bf6 21. a3 Ke7 22. Ka1 Rhb8 23. Qc4 Rb7 {with good play for Black}) 16... Qc4 17. Nxe5 Qxe2 18. Nxe2 fxe5 19. Bg5 Be7 20. Bxe7 Kxe7 21. Rd3 Rf8 22. f3 Be6 23. b3 a5 24. a4 {and Black is evidently slightly better in the ending with the superior minor piece, solid centre and initiative on the queenside. Gritty defence finally saved the draw for White after about 40 more moves in K.Beckmann-B.Vonach, Bad Wörishofen 2003 – but note that here Black got to grind in the endgame!}) (6... Bb7 {– there are no master games with this rather natural developing move: how's that for a plus? Unexplored on move six of a Ruy Lopez?? This looks quite playable: Black prepares ...d7-d6 and ...c6-c5, or even ...d7-d5 in one go, and queenside castling might be possible.}) (6... d6 {returns us directly to Chapter Six, but with an extra tempo for White. The question is, can he do anything with it? The great Lasker asked this question back in 1904 and the answer he got was: Not much!} 7. O-O Ne7 8. Nc3 ({for} 8. Bg5 {, see the next game}) 8... Ng6 9. Re1 f6 (9... c5 10. Qd3 Be7 {is easier equality}) 10. Ne2 (10. Qc4 {is best, with real chances of advantage since Black can't castle and his queenside is also under fire – though this wouldn't have happened had Lasker been more accurate on the previous move}) 10... Be6 {(you only get one chance, my friend!)} 11. Ng3 c5 12. Qc3 Be7 13. Nf5 O-O {(once again, Black has no worries about the two bishops, and stands fully equal)} 14. Ng5 Bxf5 15. exf5 fxg5 16. fxg6 hxg6 {(Lasker is quick to see the virtues of his tripled pawns – open f-file, bases for his pieces at f5 and f6 – and begins to outplay his opponent)} 17. Qd3 Rf5 18. g4 Rf7 19. Qxg6 Bf6 20. c3 Rb8 21. Re3 Qd7 22. Qh5 Re7 23. Rxe7 ({if} 23. Rh3 Re1+ 24. Kg2 Qc6+ 25. f3 Qb5 $1 {and Black's attack is more deadly}) 23... Qxe7 {(Black is clearly better, as White has no good way to develop his queenside)} 24. Bd2 Rxb2 25. Re1 Be5 26. Bxg5 Qf8 27. Bh4 Qf7 28. Qxf7+ Kxf7 29. Re3 Rc2 30. Bd8 Bxc3 31. Re7+ Kf8 32. Rxc7 Be5 {(material is still even, but Lasker has connected passed pawns on the queenside – not very likely after 4...dxc6 – and thus a clear advantage)} 33. g5 Ke8 34. Be7 d5 35. Rxc5 Rd2 $1 36. Ra5 Kxe7 37. Kg2 Ke6 38. Rxa6+ Kf5 39. h4 Bd4 40. Ra8 Kg4 41. Rf8 Rxa2 42. Rf7 Rxf2+ $1 {(Emanuel is too cool for school)} 43. Rxf2 Bxf2 44. Kxf2 Kxh4 45. Ke3 Kxg5 {0-1 A.W.Fox-Em.Lasker, Cambridge Springs 1904.}) 7. O-O ({Timothy Taylor: 'Alekhine recommended'} 7. e5 {Timothy Taylor: 'here, with a pawn sacrifice on the next move, which is probably best – White needs to keep the queens on if he is to have any hope of advantage (completely contrary to the main line Exchange, where White wants to exchange queens – you can see how this line will disconcert your opponent). After'} Qg6 8. O-O Qxc2 {Timothy Taylor: '(I don't think Black should take this, though he wins the following game)'} ({Timothy Taylor: '. Instead of this risky pawn capture, Black should play'} 8... Bb7 $142 {Timothy Taylor: ', when White has various tries but nothing particularly convincing:'} 9. e6 $2 {Timothy Taylor: 'looks strong but has a brilliant refutation:'} (9. Z0) (9. c4 O-O-O 10. Bf4 c5 11. Qe3 Ne7 12. Bg3 Nf5 13. Qf4 h5 14. h4 Be7 {and Black had good play in M.Muhutdinov-A.Lutikov, Sverdlovsk 1957.}) (9. Nbd2 O-O-O 10. Nb3 c5 11. Qc3 f6 {with approximate equality according to Keres, citing the game N.Krogius-A.Lutikov, Leningrad 1955. I found this note in Keres' book 'Spanisch bis Französisch', where he says of 4...bxc6 that there is no convincing way for White to obtain advantage against it!}) (9. Bf4 Ne7 10. Rd1 O-O-O 11. Nbd2 Nd5 12. Bg3 c5 13. Qc4 h5 14. h4 Be7 15. Re1 f5 16. exf6 gxf6 17. Qb3 Rh7 18. Rad1 Nb4 19. c3 Nc6 {, and in this violently double-edged position a draw was agreed: ½-½ R.Vera Gonzalez-F.Perez Perez, Havana 1978. As far as I can see, Black holds his own, even with the queens on.} (19... Z0)) 9... fxe6 10. Ne5 $2 Qxg2+ $1 {Keres} 11. Kxg2 c5+ {and wins.}) (8... Z0) 9. Nc3 Bb7 (9... Ne7 10. Re1 {(White has good development and central compensation for the pawn)} Qg6 11. Bg5 Qe6 12. Ne4 Nf5 13. Qc3 Be7 14. Nf6+ $5 (14. Bxe7 $1 {is even stronger}) 14... Kf8 15. g4 h6 16. gxf5 Qxf5 {, and now White can get a winning position with} 17. Nxd7+ $1 ({instead of} 17. Bh4 {, when White went slowly downhill and eventually lost in H.Daurelle-A.Sermier, French Team Championship 2003}) 17... Bxd7 ({or} 17... Qxd7 18. e6 fxe6 19. Ne5) 18. Bxe7+ Kxe7 19. Nd4 Qg4+ 20. Kh1 {, since Black's king is too exposed.}) 10. Bf4 c5 11. Qe3 Nh6 12. Bxh6 gxh6 13. Nh4 {+- Katona,F-Bouwer/corr 1977}) 7... Qxd4 8. Nxd4 Rb8 $1 {Timothy Taylor: 'One can already say that Black has equality, with the two bishops (while the white cleric is at least temporarily prevented from moving) and pressure down the b-file.'} 9. Nb3 Ne7 $1 (9... Nf6 $6 10. Bf4 d6 11. Re1 {[%cal Ye4e5] e5}) 10. Bd2 Ng6 11. Bc3 Nf4 {[%cal Yf4e2,Re2c3] Se2-c3} 12. Re1 Be7 {Timothy Taylor: '!' '!'} 13. N1d2 ({Not} 13. Bxg7 $2 Rg8 14. Bc3 Nxg2 {and Black has a strong attack even without queens.}) 13... O-O 14. Nc4 Re8 $6 (14... d6 15. Nca5 Bd7 16. Nd4 {Timothy Taylor: 'etc. Nonetheless, this is a theoretical success for Black, and the draw is not at all obvious and even perhaps dodgeable, if Black is willing to give up his bishop pair. In any case, I'll take this – where White must push accurately to maybe draw – to almost any main line Exchange, where Black must suffer for hours to reach the same result.'} Rb6 17. Nc4 Rbb8 $11) 15. Nca5 Bf8 16. Rad1 c5 17. e5 $1 Ne6 {Timothy Taylor: 'Black has a very cramped game (yes, plus equals according to Mr. Fritz!), but it's also hard to find anything to attack. Amazingly enough, Alekhine finds a way to attack out of this position with Black, though White could have avoided the combination to come with a timely a2-a3.'} (17... d6 18. exd6 Rxe1+ 19. Rxe1 cxd6 20. Re8 $14 {Alekhine}) 18. Nc4 h6 $1 19. h4 (19. g3 Ng5 20. Re3 Bb7 21. Rxd7 Nf3+ 22. Kf1 Nxh2+ 23. Ke2 Ng4 24. Red3 Rbc8 $15 {Alekhine}) 19... Be7 20. g3 g5 21. hxg5 hxg5 22. Nba5 $6 Kh7 $1 23. Kg2 Kg6 24. Rh1 $2 ({Timothy Taylor: 'Here'} 24. a3 $1 {Timothy Taylor: 'is best, when'} Rh8 {maintains the status quo of a very slight edge to White – though I don't see how Duras could really improve his position. White's actual move looks logical but allows a hidden and spectacular blow, based on the heretofore unseen power of Black's unopposed light-squared bishop.}) 24... Nd4 $1 {Timothy Taylor: '!!' '!!'} 25. Bxd4 (25. Rd2 Nb5 26. Rd3 Nxc3 27. Rxc3 {Alekhine}) (25. Ne3 d6 $1 {Alekhine}) 25... cxd4 26. Rxd4 Bb4 {Timothy Taylor: '!' '!' Timothy Taylor: 'The hidden point, which White could have prevented with 24 a3 – now Black threatens to take a knight on a5, after which he will be able to capture either White's e- or b-pawn.'} 27. Nb3 d5 $1 {Timothy Taylor: 'The second point: if the pawn is taken either way, Black's light-squared bishop becomes amazingly powerful, as the next note demonstrates.'} 28. Ne3 ({Timothy Taylor: 'but harder to see is'} 28. exd6 Bb7+ {Timothy Taylor: '!'} 29. f3 Re2+ 30. Kf1 (30. Kg1 Rbe8 31. Rh2 Re1+ 32. Kg2 f5 33. d7 R8e2+ 34. Kh3 Bxf3 $1 {, and now White must try} 35. g4 ({it's clear that} 35. d8=Q {loses straight away to} Rxh2+ 36. Kxh2 Rh1#) 35... Bxg4+ 36. Rxg4 fxg4+ 37. Kxg4 Be7 {, when Black stops the passed pawn with advantage.}) 30... Rbe8 $17 {Alekhine}) ({Obviously if} 28. Rxd5 Bb7 {wins the exchange}) {Timothy Taylor: 'for if'} 28... c5 {Timothy Taylor: '!' '!' Timothy Taylor: 'The third point, winning material;'} (28... Rxe5 $6 29. a3 Bd6 30. Nxd5 Bb7 31. Rhd1 {Alekhine}) 29. Rxd5 $1 (29. Rdd1 d4 {Timothy Taylor: ', levering open the long diagonal, is too strong.'} 30. Nc4 Bb7+ 31. f3 Bd5 32. Nd6 Rxe5 $19 {Alekhine}) 29... Bb7 30. c4 $1 (30. f4 c4 $1) 30... Rxe5 31. a3 $1 Bxa3 $1 32. Na5 Bxd5+ 33. cxd5 Rxe3 $1 {Timothy Taylor: 'In view of numerous threatened knight forks, Alekhine gives back the exchange at once to reach a pawn up ending with the superior minor piece.'} 34. fxe3 Rxb2+ 35. Kf3 f5 {Timothy Taylor: '!' '!'} 36. g4 ({Timothy Taylor: 'and'} 36. Nc4 $2 g4+ 37. Kf4 Rb4 $19 {Timothy Taylor: '– the key tactical motif is the pin on the fourth rank.'}) ({Timothy Taylor: 'Black wins after both'} 36. d6 g4+ 37. Kf4 c4 $1 $19 {Alekhine} 38. d7 $4 (38. Ke5 Rb5+) 38... Bd6#) 36... fxg4+ 37. Ke4 (37. Kxg4 c4 $19 {Alekhine} (37... Rb4+ 38. Kg3 (38. Kf3 g4+) 38... Bb2 $17) 38. Ra1 $145 $1 $13) 37... Rb4+ 38. Kd3 (38. Ke5 $2 c4 39. Kd4 Bb2+ $19 {Alekhine}) 38... Bb2 39. d6 Bf6 40. Rf1 g3 41. d7 Rb8 42. Rd1 (42. Nc6 g2 43. Rg1 (43. Rxf6+ Kxf6 44. Nxb8 Ke7 45. Nc6+ Kxd7 46. Ne5+ Ke6 47. Nf3 g4 48. Ng1 Ke5 $19 {Timothy Taylor: 'is a beautiful win given by Alekhine.'}) 43... Rb7 $19 {Alekhine}) 42... g2 {Timothy Taylor: 'Now Black wins technically, much as I did in Hughes-Taylor – with the black g-pawn on the seventh rank, the rook can easily "sacrifice" itself.'} 43. Ke2 Rb2+ 44. Kf3 Rd2 {Timothy Taylor: '!' '!'} 45. Rg1 Rxd7 46. Rxg2 Rd3 47. Rc2 Rc3 48. Rxc3 Bxc3 49. Nc4 a5 50. Nb6 Kf5 (50... Bb4 {. As Alekhine remarks, the black king simply marches to the queenside. White failed to achieve any opening advantage, and even when Alekhine riskily played for a win, the slight plus White had was never enough to give real winning chances – whereas the resources in Black's position (the two bishops especially) allowed his later combination after an infinitesimal White slip.}) 51. e4+ Ke5 52. Nc4+ Kd4 53. Nd6 Kd3 54. Nb7 Bb4 55. e5 c4 56. e6 c3 57. Nxa5 c2 58. Nb3 Kc3 59. Nc1 Kd2 0-1


